WebSocket connections fail silently when corporate proxies or misconfigured load balancers don't support the HTTP Upgrade mechanism.

**Error symptoms:**
```
WebSocket connection to 'wss://api.myapp.com/ws' failed:
Error during WebSocket handshake: Unexpected response code: 400
```

Or the connection opens but immediately closes with code 1006 (abnormal closure).

**Fix 1 — Nginx load balancer configuration:**
```nginx
server {
    listen 443 ssl;
    server_name api.myapp.com;

    location /ws {
        proxy_pass http://backend;
        proxy_http_version 1.1;
        proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;  # Required for WebSocket
        proxy_set_header Connection "upgrade";   # Required for WebSocket
        proxy_set_header Host $host;
        proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
        proxy_read_timeout 86400s;  # Prevent timeout disconnect
        proxy_send_timeout 86400s;
    }
}
```

**Fix 2 — AWS ALB WebSocket support:**
```typescript
// ALB supports WebSocket natively on HTTP/HTTPS listeners
// But the idle timeout must be increased
// CDK:
const alb = new elbv2.ApplicationLoadBalancer(this, 'ALB', { vpc });
alb.setAttribute('idle_timeout.timeout_seconds', '3600');

// Target group must use HTTP (not HTTPS) for WebSocket backends
const targetGroup = new elbv2.ApplicationTargetGroup(this, 'TG', {
  protocol: elbv2.ApplicationProtocol.HTTP,
  healthCheck: {
    path: '/health',
    interval: cdk.Duration.seconds(30),
  },
});
```

**Fix 3 — Fallback to SSE or long polling:**
```typescript
// Socket.IO automatically falls back
import { io } from 'socket.io-client';

const socket = io('https://api.myapp.com', {
  transports: ['websocket', 'polling'],  // Try WebSocket first, fall back to polling
  upgrade: true,
});
```

Some corporate proxies strip the `Upgrade` header from HTTP requests. If you can't control the proxy, use SSE (Server-Sent Events) as a fallback — it works over standard HTTP and doesn't require the Upgrade mechanism. CloudFlare and Vercel both proxy WebSocket connections correctly.

BroadcastChannel provides simple cross-tab messaging without the complexity of SharedWorker. Available in all modern browsers including Safari.

```typescript
// lib/cross-tab.ts
type CrossTabMessage =
  | { type: 'AUTH_CHANGE'; payload: { userId: string | null } }
  | { type: 'THEME_CHANGE'; payload: { theme: 'light' | 'dark' } }
  | { type: 'CACHE_INVALIDATE'; payload: { keys: string[] } }
  | { type: 'TAB_PING'; payload: { tabId: string } };

class CrossTabChannel {
  private channel: BroadcastChannel;
  private listeners = new Map<string, Set<(payload: any) => void>>();
  readonly tabId = crypto.randomUUID();

  constructor(channelName = 'myapp') {
    this.channel = new BroadcastChannel(channelName);
    this.channel.onmessage = (event: MessageEvent<CrossTabMessage>) => {
      const handlers = this.listeners.get(event.data.type);
      handlers?.forEach(handler => handler(event.data.payload));
    };
  }

  send(message: CrossTabMessage) {
    this.channel.postMessage(message);
  }

  on<T extends CrossTabMessage['type']>(
    type: T,
    handler: (payload: Extract<CrossTabMessage, { type: T }>['payload']) => void
  ) {
    if (!this.listeners.has(type)) this.listeners.set(type, new Set());
    this.listeners.get(type)!.add(handler);
    return () => this.listeners.get(type)?.delete(handler);
  }

  close() {
    this.channel.close();
  }
}

export const crossTab = new CrossTabChannel();
```

```typescript
// Usage in React
import { useEffect } from 'react';
import { crossTab } from '@/lib/cross-tab';

// Sync auth state across tabs
export function useAuthSync() {
  useEffect(() => {
    const unsubscribe = crossTab.on('AUTH_CHANGE', ({ userId }) => {
      if (!userId) {
        // User signed out in another tab
        window.location.href = '/login';
      }
    });
    return unsubscribe;
  }, []);
}

// On sign out, notify all tabs
async function signOut() {
  await fetch('/api/auth/signout', { method: 'POST' });
  crossTab.send({ type: 'AUTH_CHANGE', payload: { userId: null } });
  window.location.href = '/login';
}

// Sync theme changes
crossTab.on('THEME_CHANGE', ({ theme }) => {
  document.documentElement.classList.toggle('dark', theme === 'dark');
});
```

BroadcastChannel messages only reach other tabs on the same origin. The sender does not receive its own messages. It's simpler than SharedWorker but can only pass messages — no shared state. Messages are fire-and-forget (no delivery confirmation).

Implement rate limiting at the edge using Cloudflare Workers and KV or Durable Objects for state.

```typescript
// Rate limiting with KV (simple, eventually consistent)
import { Hono } from 'hono';

type Bindings = { RATE_LIMIT: KVNamespace };

const app = new Hono<{ Bindings: Bindings }>();

interface RateLimitEntry {
  count: number;
  resetAt: number;
}

async function checkRateLimit(
  kv: KVNamespace,
  key: string,
  limit: number,
  windowSeconds: number
): Promise<{ allowed: boolean; remaining: number; resetAt: number }> {
  const now = Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000);
  const windowKey = `rate:${key}:${Math.floor(now / windowSeconds)}`;

  const entry = await kv.get<RateLimitEntry>(windowKey, 'json');
  const currentCount = entry?.count ?? 0;
  const resetAt = (Math.floor(now / windowSeconds) + 1) * windowSeconds;

  if (currentCount >= limit) {
    return { allowed: false, remaining: 0, resetAt };
  }

  // Increment counter
  await kv.put(windowKey, JSON.stringify({
    count: currentCount + 1,
    resetAt,
  }), { expirationTtl: windowSeconds * 2 });

  return {
    allowed: true,
    remaining: limit - currentCount - 1,
    resetAt,
  };
}

// Middleware
app.use('/api/*', async (c, next) => {
  const ip = c.req.header('cf-connecting-ip') || 'unknown';
  const result = await checkRateLimit(c.env.RATE_LIMIT, ip, 100, 60); // 100 req/min

  c.header('X-RateLimit-Limit', '100');
  c.header('X-RateLimit-Remaining', String(result.remaining));
  c.header('X-RateLimit-Reset', String(result.resetAt));

  if (!result.allowed) {
    return c.json({ error: 'Rate limit exceeded' }, 429);
  }

  await next();
});

app.get('/api/data', (c) => c.json({ message: 'ok' }));

export default app;
```

**For stricter rate limiting, use Durable Objects:**
```typescript
export class RateLimiter {
  private state: DurableObjectState;
  private requests: number[] = [];

  constructor(state: DurableObjectState) {
    this.state = state;
  }

  async fetch(request: Request): Promise<Response> {
    const now = Date.now();
    const windowMs = 60000; // 1 minute
    const limit = 100;

    // Remove old requests
    this.requests = this.requests.filter(t => t > now - windowMs);

    if (this.requests.length >= limit) {
      return new Response('Rate limited', { status: 429 });
    }

    this.requests.push(now);
    return new Response('OK');
  }
}
```

KV-based rate limiting is eventually consistent (might allow slight overages). Durable Objects provide strongly consistent counting but add latency since the request must route to the DO's location. For most API rate limiting, KV is sufficient.
